        <Parent_String>guitars [300042025], lutelike chordophones with long neck: plucked [300222180], lutelike chordophones: plucked [300211801], lutelike chordophones [300224192], chordophones [300041641], sound devices by acoustical characteristics [300041621], sound devices (equipment) [300387677], Sound Devices (hierarchy name) [300041619], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Guitars of southern Italy, known from the 17th and 18th centuries, having a deep body, slightly arched back, rounded edges, slight waist, and central soundhole filled with an ornamental rose. The metal strings, usually arranged in five double or triple courses, pass over the bridge to pins at the base of the body, and are played with a plectrum.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Guitarras del sur de Italia, conocidas desde los siglos XVII y XVIII, con un cuerpo profundo, reverso ligeramente abombado, bordes redondeados, una cintura suave y una abertura acústica central cubierta con una rosa ornamental. Las cuerdas metálicas, generalmente organizadas en cinco órdenes dobles o triples, pasan encima del puente hacia clavijas en la base del cuerpo, y se tocan con un plectro.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Gitaren uit het zuiden van Italië, bekend uit 17e en 18e eeuw, met een diepe klankkast, een licht gewelfd onderblad, afgeronde zijkanten en een klankgat in het midden gevuld met een ornamentele rozet. De metalen snaren, meestal gerangschikt in vijf dubbele of driedubbele snarenkoren liepen over de kam naar pennen aan de onderkant van de klankkast en werden met een plectrum bespeeld.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052452/Encyclopedie van muziekinstrumenten (1977)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>自十七和十八世紀始知名的南義大利吉他。巴坦特吉他琴身深、琴背微拱，邊角圓滑，微具腰身，中央音孔具有玫瑰花飾，具有五對金屬雙弦或三弦，琴弦越過琴橋固定於琴身底座上的弦拴，以琴撥彈奏。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Gitarre aus Süditalien, bekannt aus dem 17. und 18. Jahrhundert, mit einem stark gewölbten Boden, leicht gebogenem Rücken, abgerundeten Ecken, leicht tailliert und einem Schallloch in der Mitte, das mit einem Rosenornament gefüllt ist. Die Metallsaiten, gewöhnlich in fünf doppelten oder dreifachen Saitenchören angeordnet, gehen vom Steg in Stifte auf dem Grund des Korpus über; gespielt mit einem Plektrum.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
